<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Deficit Widened in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603151594 Budapest MAGYAR NEMZET in Hungarian 16 Mar 94 p 
9 </F>

<F P=103> AU1603151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MAGYAR NEMZET </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Foreign Trade Quick Balance -- </F>
Exports Decreased, Imports Increased"] 
  [Text] According to preliminary figures on foreign trade 
product turnover, imports amounted to 1,162.5 billion forints at 
current prices in 1993, some 30 percent more than the year 
before. At the same time, exports amounted to 820 billion 
forints, 3 percent less than in 1992. The balance of trade 
closed with a deficit of 342.5 billion forints or $3.6 billion. 
All this has been reported to MTI by the Central Statistical 
Office. 
  The data also show that items that do not attract payment 
obligations represented a greater than usual proportion in the 
turnover. The delivery of fighter aircraft in exchange for the 
former Soviet debt, and natural gas imports to offset the 
investment at Yamburg belonged to this group. Deliveries of 
goods in connection with products manufactured under commission 
agreements, repairs, and leasing, and material contributions to 
businesses also amounted to a significant amount. Discounting 
these, the deficit can be put at $2.3 billion. In imports, 
Germany has been overtaken by the successor states of the Soviet 
Union and it is now in second place. On comparable prices, 
imports exceeded their 1990 level by 25 percent. Within this, 
the amount of machinery imports increased more than one and a 
half times. The purchase of the Boeing passenger aircraft 
played a big role in this. The import of foodstuffs increased 
by 30 percent, and the import of materials and other consumer 
goods increased by 10 to 16 percent. 
  Exports decreased by some 10 percent. Exports decreased by 
20 percent in the first 10 months of 1993 but significantly 
increased in the last two months of the year. The decline of 
agricultural and food-processing industry exports can be gauged 
at 20 percent, while 16 percent fewer consumer goods were 
exported. The export of materials decreased by 4 percent 
compared with 1992 and the export of machinery increased by 3 
percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

