<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Britain's Major Arrives in Split </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703203394 Paris AFP in English 2014 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1703203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 17 (AFP) -- British Prime Minister 
John Major arrived in the southern Croatian port of Split late 
Thursday [17 March], stopping over before a visit to the Bosnian 
capital Sarajevo on Friday, witnesses said. 
  Major, who will be making his first visit to the Bosnian 
capital, is going to Sarajevo to show his support for the 
British general commanding UN forces in Bosnia-Herzegovina, a 
spokesman for Major's office said in London. 
  Major will meet Lieutenant General Sir Michael Rose in 
Sarajevo, and will also travel to the central Bosnian town of 
Vitez -- headquarters of British UN troops serving in Bosnia -- 
the spokesman said. 
  In Split, Major was expected to meet Yasushi Akashi, special 
representative of UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali, said 
a spokesman for the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR). 
  Major's visit comes a week after London announced it would 
send an 900 more soldiers to the former Yugoslavia, bringing to 
more than 3,000 the number of troops it has in the region. 
  Britain is the second largest contributor, behind France, to 
UNPROFOR in the former Yugoslavia. French Prime Minister 
Edouard Balladur on Sunday visited the northwestern Bosnian town 
of Bihac. 
  Major visited Bosnia previously in late 1992. 
  Earlier Thursday, a UN special envoy announced that the 
Bosnian government and Bosnian Serbs had signed an agreement to 
open roads and partially lift the two-year-old siege of Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

