<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Serbs Agree on `Blue Roads' in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703201794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1857 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1703201794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo, Mar 17 (TANJUG) -- Serbs and Moslems 
agreed on Thursday at Sarajevo Airport to open up so-called 
"blue roads" for the civilian population and humanitarian 
supplies in the area of the capital of the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina ravaged by a 23-month-old war. 
  The agreement was signed by the speaker of the Bosnian Serb 
parliament, Momcilo Krajisnik, and the deputy prime minister of 
the Moslem government in Sarajevo, Husan Muratovic, at a U.N. 
sponsored meeting. 
  The agreement provides for opening the road which links 
Sarajevo and Visoko via Vogosca, corridors linking the Sarajevo 
Serb suburbs of Lukavica and Ilidza with Sarajevo's Moslem 
suburbs of Dobrinja and Butmir as well as the bridge linking the 
suburb of Grbavica with the Moslem part of Novo Sarajevo. 
  The agreement is to take effect on March 23 and U.N. 
peace-keepers deployed in Sarajevo are to supervise its 
implementation. 
  A ceasefire has been in force between Serb and Moslem forces 
in the Sarajevo area since February 10. They have withdrawn 
their heavy weapons from an area 20 kilometers in radius around 
Sarajevo or placed them under U.N. control. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

