<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croat, Muslim Agreement on POW Exchange </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1803130694 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1200 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1803130694 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by correspondent Zdenko Vranjes] </F>
  [Excerpt] Following lengthy talks late last night, Croat 
and Muslim Bosniak representatives in Gornji Vakuf signed a 
final agreement on the release and exchange of POW's on an 
all-for-all principle. The implementation of the agreement is 
to start tomorrow, when the Muslim side is to release 73 
Croatian Defense Council [HVO] members from a prison in the 
eastern part of Mostar and 294 Croats from a prison in Bugojno, 
while the Croat side will simultaneously release 500 Muslim 
detainees from Rodoc near Mostar. 
  Two Muslim army helicopters that have been kept in 
Medjugorje 
are to be returned to the Muslim side tomorrow, or after they 
have been serviced. 
  The second part of the agreement envisages that isolated 
persons -- civilians -- should be relocated on Tuesday, 22 
March. This refers to several hundred Muslims from Rotilje near 
Kiseljak and Croats from the French UN Protection Forces 
[UNPROFOR] base in Catici near Kakanj. It has been agreed that 
on Tuesday the Muslim side should release six POW's from Gornji 
Vakuf, while the Croat side should release all prisoners from 
Ljubuski, Capljina, Prozor, and a heliport near Mostar. 
  It has also been agreed that Croat and Muslim 
representatives 
will meet again on Thursday [24 March], which is the deadline 
for the preparation of an exchange of all the POW's held by both 
sides in the area of central Bosnia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

