<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government on Liabilities to International Banks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1603191894 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1603191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Government Session"] </F>
  [Text] The Macedonian [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM] Government adopted the law on settlement of 
debts toward international institutions. According to this law, 
the firms will pay their 60 million denars debt owed to the 
international bank to the state instead. They are to settle the 
debt in eight years, with a grace period of three years and an 
annual interest rate of six percent, paid in five equal rates, 
starting from 31 March 1997. 
  The government also adopted the proposed law on changes in 
existing law on administrative taxes. This law balances 
administrative services taxes, including the state's diplomatic 
and consular representative offices abroad, with the predicted 
annual inflation of 70 percent. 
  Government members postponed the discussion on the law on 
census as the Statistics Institute submitted an incomplete 
financial report. The institute only informs of approved 
finances for the census procedure, but no formal confirmation 
has been received by any international financial institution so 
far. The census is evaluated to cost about $2.2 million and if 
the financial side is not settled in due time, it is hard to 
expect it will take place in June as planned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

