<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Defense Minister Questioned on Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703183394 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Slovak Defense Minister Pavol Kanis by </F>
unidentified correspondent in Bratislava on 16 March -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Correspondent] Minister, what basic changes can 
be expected in your sector after you have taken office? 
  [Kanis] It would not be good to speak right now about what 
could be expected in the sector. I would rather stress that I 
would like to follow up the trend whose foundations have been 
laid by Minister Andrejcak. It is the trend of the Slovak 
Republic entering the European security structures. 
  As you may well know, I was the author of [word indistinct] 
programs of the Party of the Democratic Left, which were the 
first to push through the orientation towards NATO. This fact 
may have been taken into consideration in choosing a candidate 
for the post of defense minister. 
  [Correspondent] The Slovak Republic was more successful in 
concluding agreements eastward so far. Do you envisage any 
change during your term of office? 
  [Kanis] I do not think that the republic was more successful 
eastward as the Slovak Republic has achieved many successes in 
becoming closer to Western European security structures. I 
think that the decision on Slovakia's security orientation is 
unambiguous. We only have to find appropriate (?firms) and 
appropriate ways to implement this trend to strengthen the 
integration into Western security structures. It is a political 
as well as a military and financial issue. 
  [Correspondent] Do you have any conceptual solutions ready? 
  [Kanis] It would not be very appropriate to give you a 
positive answer. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

