<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Officials React to Change in Slovak Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703062094 Prague CTK in English 2023 GMT 16 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703062094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 16 (CTK) -- Czech Prime Minister 
Vaclav Klaus told journalists on Wednesday [16 March] he could 
see no immediate reason to talk to Slovak Prime Minister Jozef 
Moravcik. 
  But he added that important negotiations on exports and 
imports of goods, particularly food, were to take place by the 
end of March. The talks need not have to be conducted by the 
premiers. They can be conducted by agriculture ministers or 
within the Customs Union Council, Klaus said. 
  On Czech Television tonight, Industry and Trade Minister 
Vladimir Dlouhy expressed interest in the new Slovak Government 
to be stable. He said he hoped the Czech and Slovak parties 
would find a common language at the March 28 session of the 
Customs Union Council in Bratislava and would succeed in finding 
ways of removing unnecessary technical obstacles to bilateral 
trade. 

</TEXT>

