<DOCNO> FBIS3-9021 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu053__a94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-053-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   News Conference With Zieleniec </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703182294 Prague CTK in English 1712 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 17 (CTK) -- Disagreement with the 
recent statement by Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev that 
Russia would like to have a certain specific status within the 
Partnership for Peace plan was pronounced at today's press 
conference given by the Czech and Ukrainian foreign ministers. 
  The Czech minister, Josef Zieleniec, said that the framework 
of the plan, which the Czech Republic signed only recently, 
should not change. In the opposite case new talks would be 
necessary. He added that the Czech Republic was satisfied with 
the current plan and did not consider any change feasible. 
  The Ukrainian minister, Anatoliy Zlenko, said he could only 
agree with Kozyrev that the plan was not a panacea. But he 
added that he believed that it was in the interest of all to 
have the same status. 
  Zlenko expressed Ukraine's wish to cooperate with the 
Visegrad Four (the Czech Republic, Hungary, Poland, and 
Slovakia). He said that such an important factor of European 
developments as Ukraine could well complement the group's 
activity. 
  Zlenko is ending a two-day visit to the Czech Republic 
today. 

</TEXT>

