<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Withholds Comment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703173694 Prague CTK in English 1701 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 17 (CTK) -- The Czech Defense Ministry 
will not comment on today's press reports that dangerous strains 
of bacteria and viruses, which were to be used in the production 
of biological weapons, are stored at several localities in the 
Czech Republic, the Ministry has informed CTK. 
  According to the press, Czechoslovakia as a member of the 
former Warsaw Pact, was charged with the development of 
bacteriological weapons. They were allegedly developed at an 
undeground center of the Military Research Institute near 
Techonin, east Bohemia. The media claimed that the bacteria and 
viruses developed in Techonin had been hidden at various 
localities in the Czech Republic. 
  The press reports said that this not only contravened the 
Czech Republic's international commitments, because the country 
had signed the Geneva convention under which states undertake 
not to develop, use and store without international agreement 
biological weapons, but also threatened the public. 

</TEXT>

