<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Czech, German Ministries Agree on Immigrants </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803071794 Prague CTK in English 2042 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1803071794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 17 (CTK) -- Czech and German Interior 
Ministry delegations agreed during their two-day talks on the 
wording of a long unresolved article in the readmission 
agreement, Czech Deputy Interior Minister Martin Fendrych, who 
led the Czech delegation in Germany, told CTK today. 
  The latest round of negotiations brought to an end two years 
of talks on the agreement governing return of illegal 
immigrants. If parliament now approves the document, Interior 
Minister Jan Ruml will sign it with his German counterpart, 
Fendrych said. Both sides hope the agreement can be signed by 
June this year. 
  The agreement provides for the establishment of an expert 
committee to oversee the proper implementation of the agreement, 
propose recommendations for the resolving of problems and 
suggest any necessary changes or additions to the original 
document. 
  The delegates agreed on a period of twelve months in which 
an 
immigrant can be returned to the country from which he (she) 
illegally crossed the Czech-German border into the destination 
country. It was also agreed that the German authorities have 
six months to find a refugee. "Informal" readmission can be 
undertaken within three days of the illegal immigrant crossing 
the border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

