<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank Official on Jan Trade Deficit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703171194 Warsaw PAP in English 1521 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD1703171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, March 17 -- In January Poland recorded a 
deficit in her foreign trade of 200 m dollars, and a slightly 
smaller deficit on her current account in the balance of 
payments (191 m dollars), according to data released Thursday by 
a Central Bank official. 
  Wlodzimierz Kicinski, head of the NBP's foreign department, 
told reporters that export earnings in January reached 1,054 bn 
dollars, up 21.6 percent on January, 1993, while payments for 
imports reached 1.25 bn dollars, up 10 percent on January last 
year. Poland's leading trade partners both in exports and 
imports were Germany, the United States, Britain, France and 
Austria. 
  Gross official reserves of foreign exchange reached 4.3 bn 
dollars in January, recording a slight increase on December, 
1993. 
  Yesterday the president of the State Foreign Investment 
Agency said he expected an inflow of foreign investment and loan 
capital to Poland as a result of the agreement signed by Poland 
with the creditor banks associated in the London Club. He put 
the expected inflow at 1 bn dollars annually. 
  In the last five years foreign investments in Poland 
totalled 
3.5 bn dollars. 

</TEXT>

