<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Politicians React to Vote </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703205894 Prague CTK in English 1956 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 17 (CTK) -- "I would never have 
dreamed it could happen," Chairman of the Democratic Left Party 
(SDL) Peter Weiss said shortly after the surprising result of 
today's election date vote in parliament, which unanimously 
approved a date at the end of September and the beginning of 
October. 
  "I was only expecting a few of the deputies from the 
Movement 
for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) to support the law on 
shortening the electoral period. It was the most beautiful 
parliamentary game in the history of Slovakia," Weiss said. 
  He added that he would like to believe that this was the 
germ 
of an election campaign which would not be a hate-filled 
struggle between political personalities, but would be a correct 
and proper competition of manifestos on how to lead Slovakia out 
of its crisis. 
  Christian Democratic Movement (KDH) Deputy Frantisek 
Miklosko 
said the voting was a clear signal that HZDS deputies, after the 
lack of success of their referendum petition (which was found 
not to contain enough proper signatures) had understood that 
calling an election through a referendum was no longer possible, 
and clearly did not have the strength to do so either. Thus 
they had chosen the strategy of deciding on one of the dates put 
forward after all, he said. 
  Chairman of the Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement 
(MKDH) Bela Bugar said it was good that the question of early 
elections was being solved in a constitutional way. This was 
the most simple and cheapest solution, he said. Another way, 
such as approving a proposal to call a referendum, would cost a 
lot of money. 
  Milan Knazko, chairman of the Alliance of Democrats of the 
Slovak Republic (AD SR) said he believed that for the deputies 
of the former government coalition this was the last possibility 
of achieving early elections. All that they had tried to do 
before was their usual "variety politics," including the 
referendum, in which (judging from the inauthentic petition 
signatures) even fairy-tale beings would take part. 
  Knazko said he hoped that by the elections his party would 
be 
able to create a stable liberal right-of-centre bloc with 
Ludovit Cernak's National Democratic Party and Moravcik and 
Roman Kovac's Democratic Union of Slovakia. 
  Chairman of the preparatory committee of the National 
Democratic Party Ludovit Cernak said he thought that the 
Meciarites had made a proper assessment of the consequences of 
not supporting the election date proposal. Refusing it would 
have meant a fiasco for them; they were trying to limit the 
damage. 
  Cernak said he was glad that, in spite of their huge 
differences, Slovak deputies had sent the world a signal that 
there were things they knew how to agree on. However, he did 
not think the Meciarites could be said to have turned over a new 
leaf, as they were still fiercely oppositional in their 
behaviour. "There was no whistling in the Slovak parliament for 
two years; now there is. Nonetheless, I am glad that the first 
step is behind us," Cernak said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

