<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac's Office Reacts to Committee Accusations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703183194 Prague CTK in English 1744 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 17 (CTK) -- Slovak President 
Michal Kovac's Office today said it considered the accusation by 
the Petition Committee that it "has desecrated the sacred 
constitutional, human and natural right of citizens to 
referendum" deplorable. 
  On Wednesday [16 March], the President's Office said that a 
referendum through which the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia 
(HZDS) wanted to solve the question of early elections, the 
validity of the mandates of the deputies who have switched 
parties and the "origin" of the money used in privatization, 
would not take place since the 350,000 signatures, which 
according to the Slovak constitution are needed for the 
president to call a referendum, were not collected. 
  The Office said that out of more than 420,000 signatures 
collected only 233,000 were valid. This statement provoked 
anger on the part of the Petition Committee established by the 
HZDS of former Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar. 
  In a statement given to CTK today, the President's Office 
said that Kovac would violate the constitution if he called a 
referendum without 350,000 valid signatures. 
  While checking the validity of the petition sheets the 
President's Office proceeded in harmony with the law on 
petitions and it considers the accusation of the illegal 
interpretation of some of its provisions untrue, deliberate and 
non-trustworthy, the statement says. 

</TEXT>

