<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Magvasi: Recovery Depends on Arms Production </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703190894 Prague CTK in English 1748 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 17 (CTK) -- The production of 
arms in Slovakia has been curbed to such an extent, that one 
cannot even speak of the restructuring of the arms industry, 
Economy Minister Peter Magvasi told CTK today. 
  Economic recovery must begin with engineering industry, the 
foundation of which was arms production, he said. It is 
necessary to draw up a production program for exportable goods 
based on existing structures, he went on. 
  "The problem of re-expanding arms production is so complex 
that it is more than illusory to speak of producing new defense 
systems," he emphasized. 
  The problem of Slovak arms producers' indebtedness was 
resolved last year by granting loans funded by the National 
Property Fund and from commercial bank reserves, but it is 
difficult for arms producers to find new creditors, Magvasi 
explained. 
  As for the firm Armex, founded by Meciar's government and 
specializing in arms trade, there exist in Slovakia more 
qualified and capable companies involved in the same activities, 
he said. Armex's activities will have to be re-evaluated in the 
context of the government's new economic policy, Magvasi said. 
  The government decides who can participate in deals on arms 
exports by requiring that arms exporters obtain licenses, he 
said, adding that he did not want to favor any particular firm. 
Obviously, most arms producers are still state property, Magvasi 
added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

