<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister Views `Three Suicidal Steps' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703182994 Prague CTK in English 1745 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703182994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 17 (CTK) -- New Finance Minister 
Rudolf Filkus today spoke about how the government would resolve 
the "three suicidal steps" that were forecast for the new 
government a few weeks ago. 
  Filkus said that currency devaluation was a matter for the 
Slovak National Bank alone, and that the government should not 
interfere. 
  The second step is the restrictive measures in the social 
sphere, upon which the International Monetary Fund (IMF) makes 
conditional the provision of credit. 
  Filkus spoke about the need to show to the outside world 
that 
the new government's actions would introduce political and 
economic stability. Until then it is possible to consider new 
discussions with the IMF with the aim of moderating the impact 
of the restrictions on the general population. 
  The third step is to begin discussions about the revision of 
the general tripartite agreement, and to look for ways to 
augment state income. The notorious 50 billion koruna (about 
$1.7 billion) state debt requires enormous interest payments 
which worsen the budget deficit still further. 
  Filkus said he saw income reserves mainly in the control of 
taxes and tariffs, adding that he did not yet have the necessary 
"prescription." 
  He also mentioned the hitherto ineffective import surcharge, 
which although having "cleansed the market for Slovak producers" 
had not succeeded in saturating the market with local products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

