<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukrainian Delegation Signs Economic Accords </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703194194 Prague CTK in English 1800 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 17 (CTK) -- Ukrainian Minister for 
External Economic Relations Oleh Slepichev and Czech Trade and 
Industry Minister Vladimir Dlouhy today signed an agreement on 
economic cooperation between their two countries. He also 
signed an agreement on the support and mutual protection of 
investments with Czech Finance Minister Ivan Kocarnik. 
  Dlouhy told reporters he considered important that the Czech 
Republic should sign accords adjusting mutual commercial 
relations with all successor states to the Soviet Union 
corresponding to the regulations of the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade. 
  A Finance Ministry spokeswoman told CTK the Czech Republic 
was bound by 16 accords signed before the Czechoslovak 
Federation split (on 1 January 1993) and it automatically 
assumed all the responsibilities resulting from them. 
  Since the split, the spokeswoman said, the Czech Republic 
has 
signed a further ten accords, which are not yet in force. The 
countries concerned are Hungary, Poland, Romania, Slovenia, 
Ukraine, Tajikistan, Thailand, Australia, Portugal, and Egypt. 
  Slepichev is a member of the Ukrainian delegation led by 
Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko and scheduled to leave the 
Czech Republic this afternoon. 

</TEXT>

