<F P=101> Bosnia-Herzegovina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic: Serbs Should Start Negotiations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703182594 Budapest MTI in English 1711 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703182594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 17 March (MTI) -- After reaching a 
cease-fire in Sarajevo and an agreement on the Croatian-Muslim 
confederation, the next step towards peace is starting talks 
with Serbia, Vice-President [Presidency member] Ejup Granic told 
MTI correspondent on Thursday [17 March]. 
  Granic felt the Serbian side should accept two 
preconditions: 
Withdrawal from the occupied territories and permitting trials 
of suspected war criminals. The Serbs should be obliged by the 
international community to start negotiations, the 
vice-president said. Slobodan Milosevic's rule over Serbia is 
not strong enough to resist the world's will for ever, he 
believed. 
  Granic ruled out a politically restored federal Yugoslavia 
yet felt successor states might grow closer again economically 
in a few years' time. 

</TEXT>

