<H3> <TI>   Hungary's Jeszenszky Visits, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Supports Canton System </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703173594 Budapest MTI in English 1618 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 17 March (MTI) -- Hungarian Foreign 
Minister Geza Jeszenszky arrived in Sarajevo this morning, the 
first member of the Hungarian Government visiting the 
Serb-besieged Bosnian capital. 
  The minister and his group were taken to the Sarajevo 
Presidential Palace in the armored tanks of UN peacekeepers to 
have talks with Bosnian Vice-President [Presidency member] Ejup 
Ganic, Foreign Minister Irsan Ljubijankic, as well as Arif 
Smajkic, minister responsible for refugees and social welfare. 
  Hungary supports a canton system in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
Long-suffering Sarajevo could show the world an example of how 
people can live together in peace, despite different national 
and religious backgrounds, Jeszenszky said. 
  Lubijankic thanked Jeszenszky for the visit and expressed 
the 
Bosnian government's willingness to expand interstate 
cooperation. 
  After official talks, Jeszenszky met representatives of 
Sarajevo's 300-strong Hungarian community, mostly connected with 
the university there, and handed over some of the aid sent for 
the Humanitarian Association of Hungarians in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 

</TEXT>

