<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bosnia-Herzegovina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungary's Jeszenszky Visits, Meets Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Says South Slav Policy Unchanged </H4>
<F P=102> AU1703210094 Budapest MTI in English 2039 GMT 17 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1703210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 17 (MTI) - "NOBODY [capitals as 
received] should think that Hungary has changed its policy on 
the South Slav [Yugoslav] region. We still strive to create 
good-neighbourly links and help ethnic Hungarian minorities get 
the institutional frameworks they need to survive," Hungarian 
Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky said on Thursday. 
  On his Sarajevo visit, Jeszenszky said peace talks would be 
more successful if held in Sarajevo, since the different sides 
would also be prompted emotionally towards reconciliation by the 
sight of suffering people and destroyed buildings. 
  "People in Sarajevo would have already starved in tens of 
thousands had Europe not helped, but the same Europe cannot 
arrange a lasting settlement," said the foreign minister. 
Everyone has an interest in the Balkans not becoming a new 
Lebanon, he added. 
  Jeszenszky restated Hungary"s principal position of not 
participating even as peacekeepers in conflicts affecting its 
neighbours. There are Hungarians in Serbia, and anything could 
be misunderstood. Requests from both Bosnian Croats and Muslims 
would have to be considered by Parliament, Jeszenszky said. 

</TEXT>

