<H3> <TI>   UN To Send Investigators </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1903185694 Paris AFP in English 1836 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1903185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, March 19 (AFP) -- Three people were 
wounded in a mortar attack on Sarajevo Saturday, in the first 
major breach of the heavy-weapon exclusion zone, the press 
service of the Moslem-dominated Bosnian government said. 
[passage omitted] 
  While there have been reports of previous violations of the 
cease-fire and the heavy weapons exclusion zone, this would 
appear to be the first time civilians had been wounded in a 
shell attack on Sarajevo since early February. The United 
Nations Protection Force could not confirm Saturday that a shell 
had been fired but said military observers had been sent to the 
site to investigate. Major Jose Labandeira, a UN spokesman, said 
that whatever the cause, it was an "isolated incident". It was 
very difficult to control all the 40 to 60 millimeter mortars 
which can be carried around by an individual, he said. 

</TEXT>

