<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Major Offers $18 Million To Rebuild Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803195794 Paris AFP in English 1947 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1803195794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, March 18 (AFP) -- Britain will provide 12 
million pounds (18 million dollars) to the costs of rebuilding 
Sarajevo, British Prime Minister John Major said Friday as he 
visited the war-scarred Bosnian capital. A total of five million 
pounds will be provided now and seven million pounds later, 
Major said. 
  The Bosnian Government has estimated the cost of 
reconstructing Sarajevo at 3.1 billion dollars. 
  Major, in Sarajevo Friday for talks with Bosnian 
Vice-President Ejup Ganic and the British commander of UN troops 
in Bosnia, Lieutenant-General Sir Michael Rose, briefly toured a 
water pumping station in the city and visited a position held by 
a Scottish contingent of UN troops. On his arrival in Sarajevo 
from the central Bosnian town of Vitez, the headquarters of the 
British contingent in the UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR), Major 
vaunted the "chance for peace" in the region and said more UN 
troops would be needed soon to monitor the emerging ceasefires. 
He later left the city by helicopter to return to the southern 
Croatian port of Split, before returning to London. 

</TEXT>

