<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liberals Criticize Draft Constitution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1703175494 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1703175494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The removal of party representatives whose parties 
have fewer than six deputies from the activities of municipal 
war presidencies is an undemocratic act and constitutes the 
first tangible proof of the totalitarianization of the political 
space in Bosnia-Herzegovina, said Rasim Kadic, president of the 
Liberal Party of Bosnia-Herzegovina, at today's news conference. 
The decision was passed by the country's Presidency on the 
proposal of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government and, in my 
opinion, it is politically conflicting. 
  Rasim Kadic warned that this means that parliamentary 
parties 
that had a smaller number of voters will be thrown out of war 
presidencies, while representatives that had not even 
participated in the elections would remain in these executive 
bodies. This is a paradox. Moreover, a part of the text of the 
draft constitution for the federal organization of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina is also considered undemocratic. The part in 
question foresees a limit of 5 percent for entering the 
parliament. According to Kadic, this is the introduction of a 
single-party system. He also said that in the majority of 
European countries this limit was set at 2 percent, and that the 
Liberal Party would demand at the Bosnia-Herzegovina Assembly 
that this provision is changed, because it limits the 
development of democracy in these areas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

