<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zenica Road Opened </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003101094 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0900 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Hajrudin Sermic report from Maglaj] </F>
  [Text] Events are developing fast in Maglaj. The most 
important news is that last night chetniks withdrew all their 
artillery pieces to the left bank of the Bosna River, to the 
positions on Mount Crni Vrh, near Teslic, where they were 
deployed before 24 June 1993, thus opening the 
Maglaj-Zepce-Zenica road, and a 15-kilometer frontline around 
Maglaj by which they kept this town under siege for more than 
nine months. UN troops are already being deployed along the 
former chetnik positions. 
  A pontoon bridge on the Bosna River near [name indistinct] 
was also dismantled last night. The Serb aggressor used the 
bridge for the transit of weapons and manpower between Mount 
Ozren and Teslic. The Croatian Defense Council has taken over 
the checkpoint on the Maglaj-Zepce road near [name indistinct) 
and UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces]-mediated negotiations on the 
joint control of the road by the Bosnia-Herzegovina Army and the 
Croatian Defense Council are in progress. It should also be 
said that the Zepce Croatian Defense Council has secured the 
return of 200 inhabitants of this town to their homes, from 
where they were evicted to Maglaj four months ago. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9094 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu054_i_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-054 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

