<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2003213694 Paris AFP in English 2111 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2003213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Zagreb, March 20 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serbs have 
agreed to a second aid convoy for the northern Bosnian Moslem 
town of Maglaj as the first one arrived Sunday, providing its 
first supplies since October, a UN official said. The new convoy 
should leave from Zagreb Monday, travelling through the 
Serb-held town of Banja Luka, said Peter Kessler, spokesman for 
the UN High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). The second 
10-truck run will provide a real test of Serb will to allow 
humanitarian aid for the 100,000 people living in the enclave, 
which has been under Serb siege since mid-1993. [passage omitted] 
  "It's wonderful, we all are very pleased, we finally 
succeeded," said Kris Janowksi, a UNHCR spokesman in Sarajevo. 
Janowski said several additional convoys are scheduled in coming 
days to assist the region's war-weary population, described in a 
recent UN report as walking skeletons. On Sunday, the Bosnian 
Serb army denied Croat reports that it was retreating from 
Maglaj to the town of Teslic, 20 kilometres (12 miles) further 
north-west. Croatian Radio said the withdrawal followed an 
ultimatum by the HVO commander in Zepce, a Croat enclave 20 
kilometres south of Maglaj. In a statement carried by the local 
Serb agency SRNA, a commander of the First Army Corps of the 
self-styled Bosnian Serb Republic described the report as "pure 
disinformation and a propaganda action by the Croat media." Serb 
forces "are not withdrawing and their heavy arms are not 
blocked," said the statement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

