<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details on Aid Convoy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2003145394 Paris AFP in English 1428 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2003145394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Zagreb, March 20 (AFP) -- An aid convoy reached 
the Moslem town of Maglaj in northern Bosnia Sunday, providing 
the first such shipment to the town's population of 16,000 since 
October, UN officials said. The nine-truck convoy, escorted by 
UN armored vehicles, was carrying 80 tonnes of food and medical 
supplies and included several doctors who hoped to bring out 
from the enclave some 20 people in need of medical attention. 
  Peter Kessler, spokesman for the UN High Commissioner for 
refugees, said the relief convoy left the town of Zenica early 
Saturday [19 March] and travelled the 70 kilometres (43 miles) 
to Maglaj without encountering any obstacles from Bosnian Serb 
troops besieging the Moslem enclave. He said the convoy reached 
Maglaj shortly after 1330 GMT only to discover a devastated city 
with only a few buildings left standing. "There are almost no 
buildings left that have not been destroyed by the Serbs," said 
Kessler. "It looks like Vukovar." Vukovar is the eastern 
Croatian city destroyed by the former Yugoslav army in 1991. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

