<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Accuse NATO Planes of `Show of Force' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003170894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1650 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2003170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Petrovac, March 20 (TANJUG) -- NATO planes on Sunday 
violated air space in a show of force over western part of the 
Bosnian Serb Republic (S.R.) by taking reconnaissance flights 
over Serb positions. The planes strafed the area, terrorizing 
the population in the areas of Kljuc, Drvar, Petrovac, 
Krupa-on-the-Una and the Serb municipality of Bihac. Moslem 
forces over the past 24 hours continuously mounted fierce 
attacks on this part of the battlefront, Bosnian Serb military 
sources have said. Serb forces keep all front lines under 
control and respond to attacks only if necessary and in case 
when their property and lives of fighters are being threatened. 
The Bosnian Serb Army has had no casualties in the fighting. 
  Moslem forces have continued regrouping on the Srbobran 
(formerly Gornji Vakuf) battlefront, in central Bosnia, Serb 
military sources said. Despite strong Moslem attacks launched on 
Srbobran from Bugojno during the past week, trucks of the United 
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) have shipped off, 
via Srbobran, 600 tonnes of food for Moslems in central Bosnia, 
the same sources said. Moslem forces have again staged 
provocations against Serb positions towards Cajnice (south of 
Mostar) and Konjic (north of Mostar), local Serb military 
sources said. In western Bosnia-Herzegovina, fierce inter-Moslem 
clashes continue between loyalists of hardline Moslem leader 
Alia Izetbegovic and his moderate rival Fikret Abdic, leader of 
the Autonomous Province of Western Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

