<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Minister on `Most Sensitive' Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1703174094 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1703174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1100 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with new Slovak Finance Minister Rudolf Filkus by </F>
an unidentified correspondent at the Bratislava Castle in 
Bratislava on 16 March--recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Correspondent] Minister, what do you regard are 
the most sensitive issues facing you in your new job? 
  [Filkus] It is certainly the budget. I am not saying that we 
shall have to revise it. We shall nonetheless have to subject 
it to an appraisal from the viewpoint of revenues and 
expenditure. The situation in sectors that are dependent solely 
on revenues they receive from the state budget, such as the 
health, educational, and cultural sectors, is especially bad. 
We shall have to take another look at them. [passage omitted] 
  The problem I shall have to start tackling beginning 
tomorrow 
is to report to the public and signal to it that I have taken 
over the economy in such a state, with such currency reserves, 
such a budget deficit, such a degree of unemployment, such a 
relationship between the growth of labor productivity and wages. 
My task will be to inform the public about macroeconomic 
options we have. 
  [Correspondent] What kind of picture have you formed about 
steps you shall have to take regarding the very burning problem 
of the stability of money? 
  [Filkus] First, I believe the center that is to look after 
the stability of money is the National Bank. It possesses basic 
macroeconomic criteria with which it can judge what to do or not 
do within the framework of the stability. You must surely have 
in mind the process of devaluation and the like. This must be 
done by the bank in accordance with its own judgement. The 
Finance Ministry ought not to interefere in this matter. The 
Finance Ministry may give assistance, but the consideration and 
decision should be made by the National Bank only in accordance 
with the criteria the bank has at its disposal. No one should 
interefere in this process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

