<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conflict Detailed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1903165594 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1903165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Dragoljub Stankic from Knin] </F>
  [Text] The assembly of the republic of Serbian Krajina 
delayed its meeting today by more than three hours. They were 
allegedly waiting for Krajina Radio and Television to carry out 
technical preparations for a live relay of the session. 
However, the situation is such that earlier disagreements 
between the government and the assembly have now reached their 
peak. This is demonstrated by the proposed agenda; it has been 
proposed to the Krajina assembly deputies to debate the already 
established prime minister-designate. Let us recall: Milan 
Martic, president of the republic of Serbian Krajina, took 
advantage of his constitutional powers and informed the assembly 
chairman in writing that he should appoint Borislav Mikelic 
prime minister-designate. Mikelic was director of the Petrinja 
Gavrilovic Combine for years and then the deputy director of the 
Progres Enterprise. Assembly Chairman Branko Vojnica is only 
supposed to inform assembly deputies of this, the debate will be 
held only after the prime minister designate informs them about 
the new cabinet. 
  The coalition of the Serbian Democratic Party of Krajina and 
the Serbian Radical Party opposed the first prime minister from 
the very beginning, so a heated argument on this is expected at 
today's session. However, the majority orientation both in Knin 
and throughout Krajina is that Borislav Mikelic should be prime 
minister-designate because of his good and correct relations 
with the Serbian leadership, as well as strong business links 
with new Serbian prime minister Mirko Marjanovic. The coalition 
of the Serbian Democratic Party of Krajina and Serbian Radicals 
want to overcome this situation by entering onto the agenda the 
formation of a parliamentary delegation that would leave for 
talks with the Serbian president. 
  Foreign Minister Slobodan Jarcevic is also expected to 
present the government's proposal for the platform for talks 
with the Croatian delegation in the Russian Embassy in Zagreb on 
22 March. 
  On the agenda are also amendments to several laws: on the 
Krajina Radio and Television, the Serbian army of Krajina, as 
well as a package of financial laws. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

