<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK President on Right to Self-Determination </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2003172294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1520 GMT 20 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2003172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kragujevac, 20 Mar (TANJUG) -- Milan Martic, 
president of the republic of Serb Krajina [RSK], told Radio 
Kragujevac today that the Serbs in the RSK will not renounce 
their right to self-determination and that "this is the minimum 
below which we will not go in any talks dealing with the fate of 
the Serb nation, including the Zagreb talks scheduled for 
Tuesday." 
  Taking part in the Hallmark of the Times program on Radio 
Kragujevac, Martic said that claims that Serbia has given up on 
Krajina are pure speculation. 
  He stressed that the talks in the Russian Embassy in Zagreb 
are useful for many reasons: They are to be held on neutral 
territory, equality in talks has been ensured and, most 
important, the door has been opened for the RSK to join 
international negotiations on the former Yugoslavia. 
  Asked about his views on the role of the Russian side, which 
is sponsoring the talks, Martic said Russian diplomacy has an 
important role in stabilizing the situation in the Balkans and 
in establishing peace. 
  He said the Washington agreement between the Muslims and 
Croats was the result of the U.S. initiative which should secure 
long-term U.S. interests in the Balkans. 
  The RSK president believes that the [Croat-Muslim] alliance 
will not last long. "The alliance will make the RSK's position 
difficult for a while, but no one can return the RSK to Croatia 
by force," Martic stressed. 
  Our fate depends most on the determination and readiness for 
further efforts and pressures which will follow both in the 
sphere of diplomacy and defense. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

