<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second Relief Convoy Sets Off for Maglaj </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103113394 Paris AFP in English 1118 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2103113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, March 21 (AFP) -- A relief convoy carrying 
94 tonnes of food and medical supplies left here Monday [21 
March] heading for the Moslem enclave of Maglaj in northern 
Bosnia, UN officials reported. 
  The 10-truck convoy was expected to cross by midday the 
Gradiska Bridge, linking Croatia and Bosnia, and continue on 
toward the beseiged enclave via Banja Luka, the main city in 
northern Bosnian under Serb control. 
  Another convoy reached the city Sunday delivering 80 tonnes 
of supplies, the first to reach the beleaguered city in five 
months. Shortly thereafter Bosnian Serb leaders had given their 
approval for another convoy to reach the city, Peter Kessler, 
spokesman for the UN High Commissioner for Refugees said. He 
said the latest convoy would amount to a real "test" on the 
Serbs' apparent willingness to allow much-needed aid to reach 
the pocket's 100,000 population. 

</TEXT>

