<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Marjanovic on New Government </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803210994 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 18 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1803210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Serbian Prime Minister Mirko Marjanovic by </F>
Spomenka Jovic in Belgrade on 18 March -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Jovic] Can I freely assume that there is 
significant optimism and faith in a more stable government? 
  [Marjanovic] Well, you see, the stability of the government 
will depend on what we manage to achieve. Times are tough, and 
had we not believed that we could achieve something, I believe 
that neither I nor my associates would not have undertaken this 
task. What is the essence? The essence is that the only strong 
elements we had as pointers that we had to apply ourselves to 
diligently in order to fully succeed lay in our belief that, 
even in conditions of sanctions, there was a possibility of 
mobilizing the mechanisms for reviving the economy. If there 
were no sanctions, this would be a completely different thing, 
and I believe that we would be able to come up with even better 
programs. However, I am convinced that we will find the 
strength to keep the dinar stable, to improve and increase 
production, at least to the extent that will keep the dinar 
stable for the time being. Once we gain a little strength, then 
we can think more seriously about the further revival of the 
economy. 
  [Jovic] I thank you for this interview, and wish you 
successful cooperation with your team and the best of luck in 
your work. 

</TEXT>

