<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Membership `Necessity' for Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1903140494 Prague CESKY DENIK in Czech 17 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1903140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CESKY DENIK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [CTK report: "Joining NATO Is a Necessity for the Czech </F>
Republic"] 
  [Text] Stara Boleslav [Central Bohemia]--According to 
Vladimir Suman (Civic Democratic Alliance), chairman of the 
parliamentary Defense and Security Committee, the Czech Republic 
cannot withstand the most outstanding security risks on its own. 
  The risks are the uncertain development in the former USSR, 
aggressive nationalism and its demonstrations, and the advance 
of organized crime, the chairman said. According to Suman, the 
war in former Yugoslavia may serve as an example that border 
changes cannot be achieved by force. Yesterday, at a meeting 
between the Committee deputies and the command officers of the 
4th Air Defense Division, Suman described joining NATO as a 
necessity for the Czech Republic because, according to him, it 
is the only way to withstand these risks. He considers 
"playing" with other possibilities to be irresponsible toward 
the citizens. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

