<F P=100> ALBANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tight Monetary Policy Restrains Inflation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2003183794 Tirana GAZETA SHQIPTARE in Albanian 20 Mar 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> AU2003183794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana GAZETA SHQIPTARE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Albanian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "New Inflation Levels in the First </F>
Months of 1994"] 
  [Text] Tirana -- The tight monetary policy expressed in a 
squeeze on credit and budget expenditure continues to bear fruit 
in restraining inflation to relatively low and acceptable levels 
under conditions of economic crisis. Data from the Statistics 
Institute show that in January 1994, the Consumer Price Index 
(CPI), which remains the main indicator of inflation in Albania, 
rose 2.02 percent compared with December 1992. In February, the 
CPI rose 1.70 percent compared with January. It seems that 
higher prices for fuel and passenger transportation tickets in 
particular led to a rise in the index. The high profit levels 
enjoyed by traders on the market also continues to exert a 
strong influence on inflation. Before reaching consumers, goods 
pass through the hands of several traders, which increases their 
price artificially. It was this phenomenon that obliged the 
government a short time ago to reverse its policy of price 
liberalization and impose a price ceiling on sugar. 
  Starting from January, the CPI will be calculated on a new 
basis. "The year used as a basis for comparison will be 1994 
instead of 1990," Statistics Institute specialists told GAZETA 
SHQIPTARE. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9146 </DOCNO>
