<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Seeking Izetbegovic's Replacement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103202094 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2103202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Branislav Bozic from Banja Luka] </F>
  [Text] Croatia is demanding from the U.S. Administration 
that [Bosnian President] Alija Izetbegovic be replaced before 
the realization of the Washington accord, which was recently 
signed by the Muslims and the Croats, begins. This was reported 
by Banja Luka radio this evening. Branislav Bozic reports: 
  [Bozic] Before the Washington agreement is realized in 
practice, according to which the Bosnian Croats and the Muslims 
would first establish a federation and then form a confederation 
with Croatia, it is necessary to replace Alija Izetbegovic. 
This condition was set to the U.S. Administration by Croatian 
President Franjo Tudjman prior to the signing of the agreement. 
This was reported by Banja Luka radio tonight, citing 
well-informed Croatian sources. The report further states that 
the White House has taken a similar stand for some time. The 
additional argument was Franjo Tudjman's explanation that he had 
replaced Mate Boban who, according to him, is an extremist among 
the Croats. 
  Not only was Tudjman promised that Alija Izetbegovic would 
be 
replaced, but, as Banja Luka radio reports, he was also told 
that Izetbegovic will be replaced by either Haris Silajdzic or 
Muhamed Sacirbey, ambassador of the Muslim government in the 
United Nations. All this, as claimed, will happen very quickly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

