<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic: Negotiations To Start With Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103180794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1600 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Norwegian Foreign Minister Godal has hosted a 
lunch for Mate Granic, vice president of the [Croatian] 
government and foreign minister. In his toast he stressed the 
shared responsibility of the international community for 
resolving the problems of the former Yugoslavia and expressed 
appreciation for Croatia's way of resolving humanitarian 
problems. He also offered further humanitarian aid and accepted 
with pleasure the Croatian minister's invitation to visit our 
country. 
  Speaking about the agreement reached in Washington, he said 
that it was very good and that it would receive positive 
reactions in Norway. Croatian Minister Mate Granic then held a 
news conference at which he explained the importance of the 
Washington agreement. He added that within the next 10 to 15 
days negotiations on Bosnia-Herzegovina's organization will also 
start with the Bosnian Serbs. At this news conference, which 
attracted a great deal of attention among Norwegian media, 
Minister Granic also explained Croatia's standpoints regarding 
the resolution of occupied areas in the Republic of Croatia. He 
stressed that the Croatian authorities are willing to give local 
autonomy to the Serbs in the protected areas as well as all 
rights in keeping with international laws. 
  Granic stressed the importance of normalization of relations 
between Zagreb and Belgrade and mutual recognition among all the 
states of the former Yugoslavia. He added that this would be 
impossible without the reintegration of the protected areas into 
Croatia. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

