<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs on `Misunderstanding' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103182194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1737 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2103182194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 21 Mar (TANJUG) -- A meeting was held in 
Pale today between Dr. Radovan Karadzic, president of the Srpska 
republic [RS], and Stanislav Galic, commander of the 
Sarajevo-Romanija corps of the RS army, on the one hand, and 
Dutch General van Baal, UN Protection Forces [UNPROFOR] chief of 
staff for former Bosnia-Herzegovina, on the other. The aim of 
the meeting was to clarify the latest controversy surrounding 
UNPROFOR accusations that a small amount of Serb heavy weapons 
was found inside the 20-km exclusion zone around Sarajevo in the 
locality of Cekrcici, north of Sarajevo and in the vicinity of 
Visoko. 
  "Today we came to the conclusion that we had used different 
maps to identify the central point inside the Sarajevo exclusion 
zone. This led to misunderstanding between UNPROFOR and the Serb 
side," General van Baal said after the talks. He went on to add 
that an agreement was reached today to "start work on defining 
the positions tomorrow," in order to identify the central point 
in the controversial zone. Meanwhile Karadzic will talk by 
phone with Yasushi Akashi, the UN secretary general's envoy. We 
were in complete agreement regarding the situation in connection 
with the weapons inside and outside this zone and I think that 
today we achieved great success in the resolution of this 
problem, General van Baal said, expressing his gratitude to the 
Serb side and President Karadzic himself for their extremely 
good cooperation and understanding. 
  Sarajevo-Romanija Corps Commander Major General Stanislav 
Galic said the meeting today was very successful. He stated 
that the misunderstanding arose due to different interpretations 
about where the center of Sarajevo is. "These misunderstandings 
have now been resolved, which is yet another illustration of the 
effective cooperation between UNPROFOR and the civilian and 
military authorities of the Srpska republic," General Galic said. 
  UNPROFOR and Srpska republic representatives also met today 
at the Bratstvo-Jedinstvo bridge which is to be reopened to 
traffic on 23 March. UNPROFOR representatives for the Sarajevo 
sector and the Serb authorities in Sarajevo have agreed on 
details and technical particulars regarding the flow of traffic 
across this very sensitive location. UNPROFOR has been carrying 
out intensive preparatory work, the necessary marking and the 
protection of the bridge, and it is indicative that on the Serb 
side of the bridge, Russian UN troops were replaced by French 
UNPROFOR soldiers this morning. 

</TEXT>

