<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   B-H Army, HVO Repel Serb Attacks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203122894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1100 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2203122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Mirudin Aldobasic] </F>
  [Text] In spite of major defeats and withdrawal from the 
occupied territories in Novi Seher, Perkovic, and Vobanice, the 
aggressor continues to engage in provocations and combat 
activities. Throughout the night as well as early this morning 
the enemy has been attacking the Tesanj-Novi Seher road and 
defense lines of the units of the 7th South Operative Group, as 
well as the settlements of (Mekis), (Karadaglije), and (Radusa) 
from its stronghold in Crni Vrh. The chetniks also attempted 
several tank and infantry attacks on the Doboj front. All these 
attacks were successfully resisted, primarily thanks to the 
soldiers of the 203d Famous Motorized Brigade Doboj-Bosnia, and 
the 110th Famous Brigade of the Croatian Defense Council Usora. 
In addition, new military hardware and manpower from Novi Seher 
have been observed arriving in this area. 
  The chetniks were also provoking the defense lines with 
small 
arms at of the [word indistinct] 207th Famous Hill Brigade, but 
naturally without any results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-9169 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu055_i_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-055 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims, Croats Continue Fighting at Mostar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2103160594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1506 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2103160594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bileca, March 21 (TANJUG) -- There is no peace 
between the Croats and Moslems in Mostar despite the Washington 
agreement on a Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia. 
  On Monday the Moslems lodged yet another protest with the 
U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR) accusing the Croats for 
violating the ceasefire in Mostar and its surroundings, said 
Sarajevo Radio in Monday. 
  Members of the Bosnian Croat armed force (HVO) without any 
provocation opened strong infantry fire on the separation lines, 
while in the central parts of the city the HVO fired from 
hand-held rocket launchers on Moslem positions, Sarajevo Radio 
said. The Moslem radio failed to say whether the Moslems had 
returned fire or if there had been any casualties. 
  A representative of the Moslem authorities on Sunday 
expressed doubt that life in Mostar would return to normal soon 
despite the Washington agreement. The Bosnian Croats and 
Moslems have for the past year been engaged in fierce battles in 
Mostar in an attempt to divide the city, from which they have 
expelled almost all the Serbs, into two ethnically clean parts. 
  The representatives of the Bosnian Moslems and Croats in 
Washington submitted to strong U.S. pressure to set up their 
federation in the territory of the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and a subsequent one with the republic of 
Croatia. 
  Political analysts believe that Washington's initiative aims 
to isolate the Bosnian Serbs and pressure them to make 
additional territorial concessions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

