<H3> <TI>   SNS Fears `Introduction of a Police Regime' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103171994 Bratislava REPUBLIKA in Slovak 18 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU2103171994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava REPUBLIKA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report: "Appeal by the Slovak National Party to the </F>
Citizens of Slovakia"] 
  [Text] Bratislava--In an appeal addressed to the citizens 
of the Slovak Republic through TA SR yesterday, the Slovak 
National Party [SNS] called on the citizens to keep calm and not 
to permit Slovakia to be defamed any further. 
  In its appeal, the SNS draws attention to the "difficult 
situation in which power has been seized by people who brought 
about destabilization and are trying to preserve this situation 
under the slogan of democracy and by inciting provocations." It 
expects a further escalation of the attacks on the Movement for 
a Democratic Slovakia [HZDS] and the SNS, and, therefore, it 
appeals to citizens not to let themselves be provoked into 
ill-considered actions, the consequence of which might be the 
introduction of a police regime and a ban on national parties. 
  "Let us hold out together. Today's situation in parliament 
does not reflect the will of the population. The SNS, in 
cooperation with the HZDS, avails itself of all political means, 
with your help and by making use of the referendum as the most 
democratic means to get rid of power people who were opposed to 
the independence of the Slovak Republic or who, after losing 
their lucrative posts, have left the political entities that 
deserve the credit for the founding of the Slovak Republic and 
for returning decisionmaking on Slovak causes into Slovak hands." 

</TEXT>

