<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Says Budget Discipline To Continue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203104794 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0929 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 22 Mar--Parliamentary democracy and market 
economy are the foundations of the current government program, 
Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak said on 22 March when addressing 
about 200 participants in an international forum in Warsaw that 
had been organized by the FINANCIAL TIMES under the slogan 
"Doing business in Poland." 
  The prime minister emphasized that his government would 
observe discipline in monetary and budget policies and that it 
would continue the privatization process, while also involving 
foreign capital. He pointed out that it was necessary to 
achieve public support for the economic reforms being 
implemented. "We want the reforms to affect not only the elite 
but also the whole of society," he said. 
  Polish President Lech Walesa, in a letter sent to forum 
participants, pointed out that "Poland has a central position 
between the East and the West, the North and the South, and, 
consequently, it must be part of the integrated continent 
because this is in the interest of the whole of Europe. Poland 
is a country of enormous possibilities and a place where good 
business can be done. To place your stakes in Poland means to 
choose success," the president added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

