<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Threatens Air Strikes Over Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103183494 Paris AFP in English 1711 GMT 21 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2103183494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Brussels, March 21 (AFP) -- NATO Monday [21 
March] demanded that Bosnian Serbs relinquish heavy weapons 
found inside the exclusion zone around Sarajevo or face 
airstrikes. 
  UN peacekeepers Sunday [20 March] discovered Serb tanks and 
other heavy armament within the 20-kilometer (12-mile) exclusion 
zone imposed by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization around 
the Bosnian capital last month. 
  A NATO spokesman said that the United Nations Protection 
Force [UNPROFOR] was involved in negotiations with the Serbs to 
settle the issue. 
  "We expect these weapons to be put under UNPROFOR control 
immediately as has been the case with other weapons in the 
exclusion zone," the spokesman said, adding: "Uncontrolled heavy 
weapons within the exclusion zone remain subject to NATO 
airstrikes in accordance with NATO's February 9 decision." 
  On that day NATO issued an ultimatum threatening airstrikes 
if the parties to the conflict -- Bosnian Serbs and Bosnian 
Government forces -- did not withdraw their heavy weapons from 
around Sarajevo or put them under UN control. 
  UNPROFOR said Sunday's discovery of four tanks, three 
anti-aircraft guns, four 105mm howitzer and 18 mortars was a 
"big violation" of the UN demilitarization plan. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

