<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Boross Asks Assembly To Back EU Application </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2203124094 Budapest MTI in English 1106 GMT 22 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2203124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 22 March (MTI) -- "Integration is the 
demand of our age, and any country failing to answer it will 
inevitably fall behind," Prime Minister Peter Boross said at the 
Tuesday [22 March] plenary session of parliament, arguing for 
submitting Hungary's bid for membership to the European Union 
[EU]. 
  "Hungary is returning to Europe. Although the EU is 
primarily based on common economic interests, the Hungarian 
Government is expecting the membership status to increase the 
country's security," Boross said. "In the long run, EU 
membership will eliminate the reason for concerns over the 
situation of Hungarian communities beyond the border, too," he 
added. 
  The prime minister said that borders would become passable 
in 
the Europe of regions, neighboring peoples would be connected 
more directly, and the common European law would guarantee 
minority rights. 
  Asked whether a referendum was intended to precede the 
admission, Boross said it would be due only after the issue 
getting on the EU agenda. Negotiations are expected to start in 
1997, and there is a chance for full membership in 1999 or the 
year 2000. 
  The current situation is favorable for submitting the bid, 
Boross said, because the EU states have just ratified the 
Maastricht treaty and can now turn to the new applicants. 
  "We have been assured of Hungary's favorable prospects. It 
would be a mistake to miss this historical opportunity," Boross 
said, asking Parliament to authorize the government to make this 
step. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

