<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Explains Army Reorganization </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1803173394 Budapest MTI in English 1445 GMT 18 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU1803173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 18 Mar (MTI) -- Defence Minister Lajos 
Fur held a press conference on Friday to introduce a recently 
published book on national defence in Hungary over the past four 
years. An oversized, overorganized, and offensive army, a 
former member of the Warsaw Treaty Organization, had to become a 
defence force, he said. 
  In recent years, the 150,000-strong staff (including civil 
employees) has shrunk by 33 percent. Simultaneously, the number 
of army officers has been cut from 27,500 to 22,000, Fur said. 
  The minister said that the army, which used to be 
concentrated in Transdanubia, had to be redeployed. 
  Airborne, rapid deployment units have been formed to meet 
the 
new kind of challenges Hungary has become exposed to, mainly by 
the war in former Yugoslavia, he continued. There are now 
national defence brigades and, in accord with NATO's peace 
partnership scheme, will soon start training peacekeeping 
forces, Fur said. 
  The Hungarian army used to be marked by an internationalist 
spirit, but is now a national army, the minister said. Fur said 
lack of funds holds up army technical development. 

</TEXT>

