<H3> <TI>   UN Envoy Criticizes Government's Rights Record </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2103123194 Tirana ATA in English 1136 GMT 21 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2103123194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tirana ATA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tirana, March 21 (ATA) -- "Albanians in the Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia [FYROM] are not enjoying all 
their rights. There are signs that the government of this newly 
formed state is trying to change the situation in this 
multinational country," Mazowiecki, UN envoy for human rights 
in the FYROM, said in an interview with FLAKA E VLLAZERIMIT. 
  Referring to this interview, the BBC points out that very 
few 
Albanians in this republic have been engaged in the state 
structures of this country, stressing that this this phenomenon 
in evident mostly in the government, army, police, 
administration and in different political and social 
institutions. Mr. Mazowiecki emphasized that the human rights 
situation is not good in the fields of information and education. 
  "The newly formed Macedonian state, a new member of the UNO 
[UN Organization], should respect the rights and freedoms of the 
non Macedonian people, the more so because the perspective of 
this state depends on the observation of international norms and 
laws," Mr. Mazowiecki said in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

