<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Greek `Sources' Report U.S. Military Preparations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2203141794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1340 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2203141794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, March 22 (TANJUG) -- Greece is in 
possession of information that the United States is preparing to 
open military bases in The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia 
(F.Y.R.M.) and hastily building bases in Albania, as part of 
preparations for possible NATO operations against Serbia, the 
Belgrade daily VECERNJE NOVOSTI writes on Tuesday, citing Greek 
sources. 
  The United States is hastily building its military bases and 
adapting airports near the ports of Valona and Durazzo in 
Albania, which is a part of the U.S. plan to form its militacy 
satellites in this region. The second part of the U.S. plan is 
to form military bases in the F.Y.R.M., Yorgos Harvalias, editor 
of the Greek pro-government paper ELEFTHEROS TYPOS says. 
  Harvalias claims that Americans have sent logistics experts 
to the F.Y.R.M. to restore a former Yugoslav Army base at 
Krivolak so its could accommodate some 5,000 troops. 
  The Americans need bases in Albania and in the F.Y.R.M. if 
they engage in fighting Serbia as NATO operations require two 
fronts. The mountainous region between Albania and the Serbia's 
southern province of Kosovo and Metohija does not permit of 
waging a war with infantry but from the F.Y.R.M. territory it 
would be much easier because second front is opened in this way, 
Harvalias stresses. 
  Albanian separatists in Kosovo and Metohija have attempted 
for decades to secede this Serbian province from the Yugoslav 
Republic of Serbia and joint it to neighbouring Albania. To 
achieve this aim, they are using conventional terrorist methods, 
launching attacks on members of the army and police. 
  Over the past year, provocations on the Yugoslav-Albanian 
border and illegal incursions into the territory of the F.R.Y. 
are frequent. 
  The Krivolak testing range is the best equipped military 
testing ground in Europe and the former Yugoslav Army invested 
enormous funds in it, Radovan Kecojevic, the foremost Yugoslav 
military expert for explosive devices and pyrotechnics, whose 
knowledge and innovations are appreciated around the world, says. 
  The configuration of Krivolak's terrain is such that a 
1-kilo 
watt nuclear bomb can explode on it with no adverse effects for 
the environment, Kecojevic told VECERNJE NOVOSTI on Tuesday. 
  A total of 322 U.S. troops, as part of the U.N. 
peacekeepers, 
are currently in the F.Y.R.M., and a possibility of bringing in 
additional troops is considered so that the Scandinavian 
peacekeeping contingent, currently in the F.Y.R.M., could be 
re-deployed in Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

