<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soros Gives $4 Million for Embargo Losses </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2303123294 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2303123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Gligorov and Soros Held Press </F>
Conference"] 
  [Text] The American businessman and founder of the Open 
Society Fund George Soros arrived in Skopje yesterday, as 
announced. He emphasised his 4 million dollars aid for 
Macedonia is aimed to alleviate losses resulting from the Greek 
embargo. Mr. Soros met with top-level politicians in Macedonia 
[The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] and with 
parliament groups' representatives. Yesterday afternoon he had 
a meeting with President Gligorov, followed by a joint 
press-conference. President Gligorov underlines Mr. Soros' 
contribution and his readiness to help at these difficult times 
in Macedonia. We have very useful discussions, Gligorov said, 
primarily on the embargo and possible ways to endure it, as well 
as on the media in Macedonia, possibilities on more frequent 
programs on minority languages, etc. 
  Soros condemned the embargo in front of the press, warning 
against a possible wider conflict in the region to involve 
neighbouring countries, unless the embargo is lifted. Those are 
the reasons, he explained, Macedonia presently needs economic 
aid to survive. 
  Asked by Greek paper "Elefterothipia" whether he would send 
a 
letter to UN mediator Cyrus Vance in the same way Athens did, 
President Gligorov answered positively. Mr. Soros stated he had 
not had an did not plan any contacts with the Greek government 
at present. 

</TEXT>

